"Blanke M., Kunz A.","Effect of climate change on pome fruit phenology at Klein-Altendorf - based on 50 years of meteorological and phenological records [Einfluss rezenter Klimaveränderungen auf die Phänologie bei Kernobst am Standort Klein-Altendorf - anhand 50-jähriger Aufzeichnungen]",2009,"Erwerbs-Obstbau","51","3",,"101","114",,,10.1007/s10341-009-0086-3,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77349104599&partnerID=40&md5=63847cb54be81cbe6efd45568beed210","Universität Bonn, INRES-Gartenbauwissenschaft, Campus Klein-Altendorf, Auf dem Hügel 6, 53121 Bonn, Germany","Blanke, M., Universität Bonn, INRES-Gartenbauwissenschaft, Campus Klein-Altendorf, Auf dem Hügel 6, 53121 Bonn, Germany; Kunz, A., Universität Bonn, INRES-Gartenbauwissenschaft, Campus Klein-Altendorf, Auf dem Hügel 6, 53121 Bonn, Germany","This project examines the effects of climate change on pome fruit phenology at Klein-Altendorf in the Rhineland fruit-growing region in the West of Germany, using 50 years of weather data and phenology records, including beginning of flowering (F1), full bloom (F2), harvest date and leaf drop of apple and pear, with the following results: 1. Fifty years of weather records and pome phenology data showed a distinct separation between a first phase (1958-1987), which was 0.42°C cooler, and a second phase (1988-2007), which was 0.66°C warmer than the long-term, 50 year temperature average of 9.4°C, indicating the start of the climate change in 1988. 2. Annual average temperatures rose from 8.8°C to 10.2°C, i.e. by 1.4°C over 50 years at Klein-Altendorf, which affected the apple phenology. A comparison of the second phase (average temp. 10.1°C) with the first phase (9.0°C) resulted in a temperature rise of 1.1°C; the temperature rise in the winter (1.2°C) was greater (by 0.2°C) than in the summer (1.0°C). This temperature rise in the last 20 years (second phase, 1988-2007) was more pronounced in the winter months January (+1.7°C) and February (+1.8°C) than in the spring months March and May both with +1.4°C leading to enhanced early post-bloom fruit drop, and July (+1.3°C) and August (+1.6°C). 3. Annual precipitation remained constant at ca. 600 mm with an increase in February, March and April and an equivalent decrease in May (-10 mm) and July (-7 mm) during fruit development. 4. Soil temperatures increased by 2.6°C and hence greater than the air temperature (+1.45°C) over the last 50 years; this increase was most pronounced between January and March. 5. Minimum air temperatures increased also by 2.6°C from -6.1°C in March 1958 to -3.5°C in March 2007. The more advanced flowering, brought about by warmer January to March temperatures, now coincides with late spring frosts, thereby maintaining the risk of yield loss due to spring frost in April, a month when the minimum temperature still continues to drop. 6. On average, apple and pear flowering was 10 days earlier without extension of the flowering period after warm winters and appeared more severely affected than the harvest period (3-9 days) and leaf drop (2-3 days earlier) with distinct varietal differences. The apple flowering period was 4 days shorter in the last 10 years and reduced from 12-15 days to 8-10 days. Early maturing cultivars (cvs) ripened 3-4 days earlier, while late cvs ripened 8-12 days earlier. The period between harvest and leaf drop was extended by 2-7 (apple) to 11 days (pear), which requires regional differentiation according to the respective climatic zone and may be beneficial for nutrient translocation into the perennial woody parts of the tree. 7. Since the changes in the temperature-based vegetation period did not explain the effects of climate change on pome phenology, a 'pomological vegetation interval' between the beginning of flowering and beginning of leaf drop was defined and was extended by climate change in spring by 0-10 days in apple and by 8 days in pear. Based on flowering (F1, F2) advances, the Meckenheim fruit-growing region was more strongly affected by the climate change compared with other European fruit growing regions. © Springer-Verlag 2009.","Apple; Climate change; Flowering date; Full bloom; Global warming; Growing period; Harvest date; Leaf drop; Phenology","Malus x domestica; Pyrus",,,,,,"Atkinson, C., Taylor, L., The influence of autumn temperature on flowering time and cropping of Pyrus communis cv. 'Conference' (1994) J Hort Sci, 69, pp. 1067-1075; Bergamaschi, M., Giovanni, D., Liverani, A., Sirri, S., Influence of climate on flowering phenology of pome and stone fruit in Romagna, Italy (2008) European Hort, pp. 111-112. , Congress She, Wien, Februar 2008; Burroughs, W.J., (2007) Climate Change, , 2nd edn., Cambridge: Cambridge University Press; Chen, K., Lenz, F., Effects of doubled atmospheric CO2 concentration on apple trees. IV. Water Consumption (2002) Gartenbauwissenschaft - Eur J Hort Sci, 67, pp. 99-106; Chmielewski, F.-M., Avocado statt Pflaumen - Sind für den Steinobstanbau Veränderungen durch den Klimawandel zu erwarten? (2007) Vorträge zum 33, pp. 9-26. , In: DLR (Hrsg.), Bundessteinobstseminar in Ahrweiler, 4. Dezember 2007; Chmielewski, F.-M., Blümel, K., Henniges, Y., Müller, A., Klimawandel und Obstbau in Deutschland (KliO) (2008) 2. projektspezifischer Teilbericht des BMBF-Verbundprojekts KliO, p. 124. , http://www.agrar.hu-berlin.de/agrarmet/forschung/fp/KliO_html; Chmielewski, F.-M., Müller, A., Bruns, E., Climate changes and trends in phenology of fruit trees and field crops in Germany 1961-2000 (2004) Agric For Meteorol, 121 (1-2), pp. 69-78; Chmielewski, F.-M., Müller, A., Küchler, W., Climate changes and frost hazard for fruit trees (2005) Annal Meteorol, 41 (2), pp. 488-491; Chmielewski, F.-M., Rötzer, T., Response of tree phenology to climate change across Europe (2001) Agric For Meteorol, 108, pp. 101-112; Debontridder, L., Climate change - myth or reality? Climate change: Challenges, risks and impacts on horticultural cropping systems (2009) Jahrestagung der Benelux Society of Horticulural Science, p. 3. , Gembloux, Belgen, 3. April 2009, Abstractheft; Domergue, M., Legave, J.M., Calleja, M., Moutier, N., Brisson, N., Seguin, B., Réchauffement climatique et conséquences sur la floraison (2004) L'arboriculture Fruitière, 578, pp. 27-33; Görgens, M., Weber, R., (2007) Klimawandel im Obstbau, p. 186. , Vortrag DGG Erfurt, Februar 2007. Schriftenreihe des BGDL, Band 43; Hammond, M.W., Seeley, S.D., Spring bud development of Malus and Prunus species in relation to soil temperature (1978) J Am Soc Hort Sci, 103, pp. 655-657; Henniges, Y., Vollmer, I., Weber, R.W.S., Görgens, M., Chmielewski, F.M., Der Klimawandel, eine Herausforderung für den norddeutschen Obstbau (2007) Mitt OVR, 62 (5), pp. 147-151; Jones, H.G., Possible effects of climate change on soft fruit production: The example of winter chill in Ribes (2008) Workshop on ""Berry Production in Changing Climate Conditions and Cultivation Systems."", , Book of Abstracts. COST Meeting Geisenheim 29.-31. October 2008; Kajfez Bogataj, L., (2008) Climate Change and Fruit Adaptation, pp. 91-102. , Obstbaukongress Krsko 31. Januar bis 2. Februar 2008, Tagungsband; Kers, M., (2009) persönliche Mitteilung; Kolbe, W., (1965) Beziehungen zwischen Klima, Obstbau und Pflanzenschutz - Rückblick auf 25 Jahre Höfchen, , Pflanzenschutz Nachrichten Bayer, Sonderheft zum 25jährigen Bestehen des Versuchsgutes Höfchen, Veröffentlichungen der Farbenfabriken Bayer AG Leverkusen (früher ""Höfchen-Briefe""); Kromb-Kolb, H., (2008) The Causes and the Extent of Climate Change - Past and Present, p. 86. , www.she2008.org, She Congress Wien, Feb. 2008; Krüger, E., Climate change and performance of strawberry at Geisenheim (2008) Workshop on ""Berry Production in Changing Climate Conditions and Cultivation Systems"", , Book of Abstracts. COST Meeting Geisenheim 29.-31. October 2008; Küchler, W., (2007) Klimawandel in Sachsen, , www.landwirtschaft,Sachsen.de/lfl, Pillnitzer Obstbautage 